sentences: Héctor Juan Pedro Bosio Bertolotti (born 1 October 1958) better known by his stage name Zeta Bosio, is an Argentine rock musician, record producer and disc jockey (DJ), better known as the bassist of the Argentine rock band Soda Stereo.
He was also the bassist of Chilean band La Ley between 2013 and 2014.
Bosio, along with Gustavo Cerati and Charly Alberti, formed Soda Stereo in 1982.
They recorded over a dozen records until they disbanded in 1997.
In 2011, he was a judge in the Chilean TV show Factor X.
In 1979, Zeta met Gustavo Cerati in college, but they did not become friends.
During the summer of 1982, they met again at Punta del Este (Uruguay), Cerati with his group Sauvage and Bosio with The Morgan.
Soda Stereo was formed there, and debuted in July 1983.

Soda Stereo was dissolved in September 1997 and subsequently Zeta worked with other groups, first through the web Under Project, then as manager of Sony Music Argentina, and in more recent years with Alert Discos.
In June 2007, Soda Stereo announced their comeback with a tour.
In 2008, Zeta and his companions in Soda Stereo returned to their own projects after their brief reunion.
Zeta participated in the Lollapalooza festival, held for the first time outside the US, in Chile in April 2011.
In 2013, Zeta joined Chilean band La Ley as bassist.

Nowadays he plays in the band Shoot the Radio, which he co-founded.
Since then, he kept a low profile until quite recently.
Bosio is now working with his independent record label Alerta Discos.
They played on the student program "Happy Sunday" on Channel 9.
During the summer of 1982, they met again at Punta del Este (Uruguay), Cerati with his group Sauvage and Bosio with The Morgan.

Zeta and Gustavo shared the same musical tastes and dreams, and began a search for integrating a punk rock group inspired by The Police (who played the same year in Argentina), with their own songs in Spanish.

Shortly after Gustavo and Zeta decided to visit Charly Alberti (son of the famous percussionist Tito Alberti, who was four years younger than Bosio and three years younger than Cerati), to hear him play his father's drums.

Soda Stereo was dissolved in September 1997 and subsequently Zeta worked with other groups, first through the web Under Project, then as manager of Sony Music Argentina, and in more recent years with Alert Discos.
In 2005, 2006 and 2007, Zeta hosted a TV show called Rock Road on the Argentine channel Much Music.
Between October and December of that year, Zeta Bosio and Soda Stereo played throughout Latin America on a tour called Me Verás Volver.
